{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":10070,"record_hash":"sha256:1c7c4f5adc98763f37b300aa3a11624cf838915aba18ec9166f255ef72c4dbf1","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:46:25.495Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: c7d87d\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1882\nOutput:\n## Expected Agent Access Pattern\n\nWhen a user asks an agent to catch up with a branch, the agent should not try to\nload everything. A good workflow is:\n\n1. Resolve the current branch or requested branch.\n2. Run `but agentlog sessions branch <branch>`.\n3. Pick likely useful sessions from outline data:\n   - prefer recent sessions\n   - prefer sessions with incremental turns over one-off sidecar backfills\n   - inspect sidecar sessions only when their previews look relevant\n4. Run `but agentlog timeline <session-key> --limit 20` for the most promising\n   session.\n5. Read records from selected turns:\n   - latest incremental turns first\n   - tail of a large backfill when the backfill is the only evidence\n   - head of a backfill only if the original task prompt is unclear\n6. Read adjacent or older turns only if the first pass leaves gaps.\n\nThe agent's natural unit of navigation is the capture turn, not individual\nrecords. Records are the rendering layer once a turn has been selected.\n\nTool calls and tool results should stay visible but not dominate the workflow.\nIn practice, the agent should scan:\n\n- user messages for intent and corrections\n- assistant messages for decisions, plans, and final status\n- tool calls for files inspected, commands run, and tests attempted\n- tool results only when they contain outcomes, failures, diffs, or important\n  evidence\n\nThe CLI should make that possible by preserving ordered records and clear record\nkinds, not by deciding which record kinds are important.\n\n### Optional Later Tool: `search`\n\nSearch is useful, but not needed for the first handoff slice.\n\n```text\nbut agentlog search <query> [branch <branch> | review <review> | change <change>]\n```\n\nAdd this only after the three read tools feel insufficient on real branches.\nThe first version can be plain full-text search over redacted transcript text\nand turn metadata, returning session/turn hits that the agent can inspect with\n`\n[TRUNCATED]\nranch. Some are\nsidecar/subagent review sessions, not the main user thread.\n\nThe handoff layer should not hide these. It should make them legible:\n\n- main-looking sessions: long-running, many incremental turns, latest user asks\n- sidecar-looking sessions: one backfill, review prompt, separate provider\n  session id, often created close together\n- compacted/resumed sessions: may have a new provider session id but overlapping\n  prior conversation context\n\nAvoid hard-coding those labels until the source data supports them. For now,\nexpose enough facts for the consuming agent to decide.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- no provider-native resume\n- no generated persistent handoff summary\n- no magic `handoff` command for v1\n- no durable inferred ownership like \"this branch belongs to this session\"\n- no GitButler app API dependency for the first flow\n- no automatic transcript dumping into `but status`\n- no product-specific review browsing payloads\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- Do we need a first-class \"session outline\" primitive in `but-agentlog`, or can\n  it be assembled cheaply from existing reads?\n- Can we reliably capture provider metadata that distinguishes top-level\n  sessions from spawned subagents?\n- Should compaction/resume grouping be a later derived feature, or do we need to\n  store more source metadata now to make it possible?\n- How much transcript text should human-readable output show by default?\n\n## Recommended First Implementation Slice\n\nDo not implement \"handoff\" as one magic command.\n\nFirst add enough generic CLI read commands that an agent or skill can perform the\ncatch-up workflow:\n\n1. enhance `agentlog sessions` so JSON includes session outline fields, not just\n   keys\n2. add a bounded timeline command for one session\n3. add a bounded records command for one turn\n4. write a small skill/workflow note that tells agents how to use those commands\n\nThat keeps the feature honest. If the workflow feels clumsy after using the\nprimitives on real branches, improve the primitives rather than hiding them\nbehind an opaque command.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:46:25.495Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}